column168: METAL RINGS WERE NOT PROPERLY ATTACHED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT OF THE INNER PLASTIC BLADDER. PTL DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE TO DISCOVER ONE OF HIS 55 GALLON DRUMS HAD LEAKED.  ABOUT A QUART OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT AROUND THE CAP ON THE DRUM.  ALL THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  CONSIGNEE OVER-PACKED DRUM AND ACCEPTED THE LOAD.  DRIVER CONTINUED ON.

PTL DRIVER DISCOVERED WHEN HE OPENED TRAILER DOORS AT DELIVERY POINT THAT 2 (55 GALLON) DRUMS HAD OVERTURNED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. ONE DRUM HAD NOT LEAKED, BUT THE 2ND DRUM HAD LEAKED ABOUT 1.5 CUPS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE WOODEN FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS A 53 FT AND THE PRODUCT WAS LOADED 4 DRUMS TO A PALLET WITH NO SHRINK WRAP OR BANDING TO THE 48 FT MARK.  LOAD LOCKS HAD BEEN APPLIED, BUT THE 2 BACK DRUMS KNOCKED THE LOAD LOCKS LOOSE AND TIPPED OVER ONTO THE FLOOR.  PTL CONTACTED OUR INSURANCE COMPANY AND WHEN THE ADJUSTOR ARRIVED A CLEAN-UP COMPANY OUT OF HOUSTON, TEXAS WAS CALLED TO CLEAN-UP THE TRAILER AND THE DRIVER PROCEEDED ON TO THE NEXT LOAD.

DRIVER PICKED  UP AT CUSTOMER DOCK.  WHEN TRAILER ARRIVED BACK AT TERMINAL FREIGHT WAS UNLOADED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE CARTONS ON THE SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET WAS LEAKING INSIDE THE SHRINK WRAP.  CARTON WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN LOADED UPSIDE DOWN ON THE SHRINK WRAP SKID CAUSING PRODUCT INSIDE TO LEAK.  SHIPPER CONTACTED AND FREIGHT WAS SENT BACK TO SHIPPER FOR REPACKING.

DRIVER SPOTTED UNIT UNDER THE RACK FOR LOADING.  HE OPENED THE DOME AND PUT IN THE LOADING SPOUT.  HE SECURED THE CHAIR THAT HOLDS THE SPOUT IN THE TANK, AND AS HE STARTED THE PUMP, THE LOADING SPOUT WENT DOWN, THEN AS THE PRODUCT STARTED FLOWING THE SPOUT JERKED UPWARDS CAUSING THE S HOOK TO COME LOOSE FROM OUR TANK AND ACID GOT ONTO THE TANK, AND THE GROUND.  IT WAS IMMEDIATELY WASHED INTO THE DRAIN DUMP.

THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED AND A FIVE GALLON BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK TO COLLET SPILLAGE.  ALL REQUIRED LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE IMMEDIATELY PERFORM.  THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS NOTIFIED AT 1115 HOURS THAT SAME DAY AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE FOR IMMEDIATE REPAIR.  THE SHIPPER RESPONSE CREW ARRIVED ON SITE AND CORRECTED TWO LEAKS BY (1) REPAIRING A LOOSE LOADING VALVE LOCATED ON TOP OF THE CAR AND (2) REPAIRING A DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  UPON COMPLETION OF ALL REPAIRS AND DECONTAMINATION THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

ON JULY 2, 998 AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR GATX 300582, LOADED WITH CARBON DIOXIDE, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, WAS OBSERVED VENTING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE BY THE  LOCAL POLK COUNTY SHERIFF WHILE THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN THE KCS WICKES, ARKANSAS SIDING TRACK.  THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED A RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SITE.  WHEN THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE, THE TANK CAR VENTING HAD CONCLUDED AND THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE HAD RE-SEATED. EXPANSION OF THE LADDING CAUSED BY HOT SUMMER TEMPERATURES, POSSIBLY COMPOUNDED BY TANK CAR OVERLOADING, WAS THE DETERMINED CAUSE.  THE TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED AND OKAYED BY THE SHIPPER AND RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

UNLOADER,  DAVE BARTKEWITZ, NOTICED LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION , HE FOUND THE ORGIN OF THE SPILLAGE.  NO LABELS VISIBLE (PRESENT)  TO INDICATE WHAT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IT MIGHT BE.  THE DRUM WAS STRUCK WRAPPED WITH OTHER PAILS ON A PALLET.  THE PALLET WAS BROKEN DOWN TO FURTHER EXAMINE THE LEAKER.  AT THIS POINT, DAVE NOTICED THE POISON LABEL ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM. column168: ON JULY 2, 1998 AT 1700 HOUR WE WERE UNLOADING A DELIVERY OF GASOHOL AT  A CONVENIENCE STORE LOCATION IN ALBERT LEA, MINNESOTA.  WHEN THE DRIVER WA ALMOST FINISHED UNLOADING HIS LOAD, A SPILL OCCURRED AND HE LOST APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  WE FEEL THAT THE DRIVER WAS EITHER GIVEN AN INACCURATE READING OF THE TANK OR THERE WAS A MISTAKE IN INVENTORY.  THE ALBERT LEA FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED AS WELL AS THE MINNESOTA EPA.  WE THEN WERE INSTRUCTED TO HIRE AN EXCAVATOR TO SCOOP UP THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND GRAVEL AND PLACE ON AND COVER THE PLASTIC. AT THIS TIME WE ARE WAITING FOR  LAB RESULTS IN ORDER TO TAKE THIS PRODUCT TO A NEAR BY LANDFILL.  WE HAVE INSTRUCTED ALL OUR DRIVERS TO MONITOR TANK CAPACITY AT ALL OUR LOCATIONS,  AND RE-EMPHASIZED PROCEDURES TO FOLLOW WHEN THESE INCIDENTS OCCUR.

column168: CUSTOMER/SHIPPER WAS LOADING TRAILER FROM RAIL CAR USING A METER. THE METER FAILED TO SHUTOFF AT THE PROPER SETTING, AND THETRAILER FILLEDU AND BEGN TO OVERFLOW. A SHIPPER PERSON SHUT DOWN THE PUMP. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CAPTURED IN A CATCHMENT BASIN AND NEUTRALIZED. THE SHIPPER WASHIED OFF THE TANK TRUCK. column42: FORMIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 85% ACID BY MASS
column168: THE TRUCK WAS RETURNING FROM THE VENDOR ON THE WAY TO THE MCDONOUGH PLANT CARRYING 16 DRUMS OF FORMIC ACID WHEN THREE DRUMS FELL OVER, CRACKING ONE OF THE 55 GALLON DRUMS AND ALLOWING MOST OF THE CONTENTS TO LEAK OUT.  THE DRUMS TIPPED AS A RESULT OF THE LOAD BAR DISLODGING FROM THE TRUCK SIDE WALLS, ALLOWING THE DRUMS TO SHIFT AND TIP. THE DRIVER STOPPED THE TRUCK AND UPON OPENING THE DOOR TO INVESTIGATE THE SITUATION WAS OVERCOME BY ACID FUMES.  THE DRIVER SHUT OFF HIS TRUCK, GRABBED HIS PAPERWORK AND RESPIRATOR AND WENT TO AN ADJACENT BUSINESS AND ASKED THAT THEY CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE DRIVER WAS SENT TO THE HOSPITAL AND WAS ADMITTED FOR OVERNIGHT OBSERVATION BECAUSE THE MSDS INDICATED THAT PHYSICAL REACTIONS MAY BE DELAYED.  THE IMMEDIATE RESPONSE WAS BY THE CLAYTON COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY.  IN ADDITION, ECOLAB SENT TWO REPRESENTATIVES TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE TO THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES.  THE TRUCK WAS OFF THE ROAD AT A POINT WHERE THE ROAD SLOPED INTO A SHALLOW CULVERT WHERE THE LIQUID COLLECTED IN A PUDDLE.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP 1-800 PHONE NUMBER WAS CALLED A CREW FROM A COMPANY CALLED HEPACO WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP.  HEPACO COMPLETED THE CLEAN UP AND THE TRUCK WAS RETURNED TO ECOLAB BY ANOTHER ECOLAB FLEET DRIVER.  NEW LOAD BARS HAVE BEEN ORDERED.  ECOLAB IS FOLLOWING UP WITH THE VENDOR IN REGARDS TO THE DRUM FAILURE.
VENT ALARM INOPERABLE

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: EMPLOYEE FAILED TO SECURE THE CONNECTION OF THE HOSE TO THE TANK FITTING, CAUSING A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLON OF PRODUCT.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY KENAN PERSONNEL WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DRIVER UNLOADING INTO NEW 5,000 GALLON STORAGE TANK.  HE HAD 4,700 GALLONS TO PUT INTO THE STORAGE TANK.  AT THE SAME TIME HIS CARGO WENT EMPTY.  A SMALL AMOUNT BURPED OUT THE STORAGE TANK VENT LINE AND LANDED ON THE NEW CONCRETE PAD.  THE CONSIGNEE'S ENVIRONMENTAL DEPT. CAME OUT AND APPLIED CALCIUM CHLORIDE TO ABSORB THE SPILL AND SWEPT IT UP FOR DISPOSAL.

OUR DRIVER HAD FINISHED TRANSFERRING PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK TO STORAGE TANK.  AT APPROXIMATELY 6:45 AM, UNHOOKED HIS UNLOADING HOSES AND LEFT THE CONSIGNEE AT 0700 HOURS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 16:30 HOURS WERE WERE NOTIFIED THAT TWO CONTRACT WORKERS AT THE UNLOADING AREA INSIDE OF THE BUILDING INHALED PRODUCT FUMES AND WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT.  OUT INSPECTION INDICATES THAT THEIR SCRUBBER FOR PRODUCT FUMES COULDN'T TAKE AIR SURGE WHEN CARGO TANK WENT EMPTY AND CAUSED A VAPOR RELEASE. WE ARE TRYING TO WORK OUT A DIFFERENT UNLOADING PROCEDURE.

WHILE PARKED IN SERVICE PLAZA, STATE TROOPER NOTICED LEAK OF FLUID COMING FROM HOSE THROUGH ON LEFT SIDE OF TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION LEAK WAS COMING FROM A 20' - 2" HOSE THAT WAS NOT CAPPED PROPERLY IN THE TROUGH.  THE PRODUCT WAS RESIDUE FROM INSIDE THE HOSE.  THE HOSE CAP WAS RE AFFIXED AND SECURED.  UPON RETURN TO THE TERMINAL, THE HOSE AND CAP WERE REPAIRED AND INSPECTED AND THE AREA WAS CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED OFF BY A HAZMAT TEAM.

AFTER DRIVER RECEIVED THE OKAY TO UNLOAD, DRIVER ENGAGED TRACTOR PUMP INTO WRONG DIRECTION WHICH RESULTED IN TRANSFERRING PRODUCT FROM STORAGE TANK INTO CARGO TANK WHICH OVERFILLED OUT OF THE DOME.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED, SUCKED UP INTO DRUM AND REWORKED.

AFTER DRIVER RECEIVED THE OKAY TO UNLOAD HE STARTED UP TRACTOR PUMP AND UNLOADER SAID SOMETHING WAS WRONG WITH HIS PUMP.  DRIVER ADJUSTED BYPASS ON PUMP AND TOLD UNLOADER THAT THE PUMP WAS WORKING.  IT WAS DETERMINED CONSIGNEE'S VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE.  VALVE WAS CHANGED AND DRIVER STARTED PROCESS OF UNLOADING WHEN THEIR WARNING ALARM SYSTEM WENT ON.  DRIVER SHUT OFF PUMP.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO START UP AGAIN WHEN THEIR ALARM WENT ON.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO KEEP PUMPING. THEIR VALVE CLOSED AUTOMATICALLY WHICH CAUSED OUT HOSE END TO PRESSURE OFF OUR HOSE. CONSIGNEE SPREAD OIL DRY AND CLEANED UP AREA.

DRIVER RETURNED TO CARRIER TERMINAL FOR MECHANICAL ADJUSTMENT OF VEHICLE UNRELEASED TO THE CARGO TANK.  WHILE VEHICLE WAS BEING SERVICED, THE MECHANIC NOTICED A SINGLE DROPLET OF PRODUCT FORMING ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE CARGO TANK (NON-INSULATED TANK) AND NOTIFIED MANAGEMENT.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL INTO A DIFFERENT CARGO TANK.  THIS WAS DONE UNDER THE SUPERVISOR OF A CARRIER SUPERVISOR TRAINED TO HAZMAT TECHNICIAN LEVEL.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED WITH NO INCIDENT.  THE ORIGINAL CARGO TANK WAS CLEANED AND SENT OUT FOR TESTING AND REPAIRS.  THE DRIP WAS NOTED AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK TRUCK AT A POINT WHERE THE REINFORCING BOLSTER RINGS ARE WELDED TO THE CARGO TANK.  THERE WAS NO LOSS OF PRODUCT TO GROUND, AND NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

column168: OUTBOUND DRIVER REPORTED CONTAINER LEAKING. INSPECTION BY BNSF HAZ MAT RESPONDERS REVEALED THAT THE LEAKING DRUM WAS LOCATED ALONG THE RIGHT WALL, FOURTH STACK FROM THE FRONT. DRIVERS ARRIVED AT PLANT, WERE SENT TO TANK LOCATION TO UNLOAD. DRIVERS CHECKED SEVERAL TIMES WITH UNLOADING PERSON TO MAKE SURE THAT THEY WERE UNLOADING AT CORRECT TIME, THIS PERSON SIGNED BILLS AND DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD. WITHIN 10-15 SECONDS A HISSING SOUND AND ODOR WAS DETECTED AND A VAPOR APPEARED ABOVE TANK. DRIVER CLOSED TRAILER VALVES AND TRIED TO WARN CONTRACTORS WORKING ON AN ADJACENT TANK. DRIVER THEN CLOSED CUSTOMER VALVE AND THEN WENT TO FIND HELP.

DRUM HAD LOOSE CAP CAUSING ACID TO SPILL, MELTING SHRINK WRAP. DRUM ROLLED TO BACK OF THE TRAILER AND ACID SPILLED ON TUCKER CASTLE BERRY PROPERTY. 10 GALLONS CONTAINED BY VAN WATERS(SHIPPER) WITH SODA ASH AND OIL DRY.

DRIVER DISCOVERED A VAPOR CLOUD IN TRAILER UPON ROUTINE LOAD INSPECTION. NO MATERIAL ESCAPED OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER. A RESPONSE CREW WAS SENT AND NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO IL AND NRC. CREW DISCOVERED A LOOSE BUNG ON A DRUM CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID. ACID HAD SPLASHED ON A DRUM CONTAINING NITRIC ACID AND BOTH ACIDS LEAKED. CREW OVER DRUM AND CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL. DESIGNATED FACILITY HANDLED DISPOSAL OF SPILL DEBRIS. OCCUPANTS OF A MOTEL WERE ADVISED TO LEAVE AND ONE DRIVEWAY TO WAL-MART WAS ROPED OFF, AS WELL AT THEIR GARDEN CENTER.

OUR UNIT WAS UNDER LOADING RACK AT STEPAN CO. WHO WAS LOADING SPENT ACID INTO OUR UNIT. OUR DRIVER WHO WAS IN THE CAB AT THE TIME LOOKED INTO HIS MIRROR AND SAW LIQUID RUNNING OUT OF THE OVER FLOW SPILL TUBES AND ONTO THE LOADING PADS. HE GOT OUT AND THE LOADER WAS SHUTTING OFF HIS FILLING LINE. THE SHIPPER COVERED THE RELEASE PRODUCT WITH BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THEN FLUSHED WATER INTO THEIR CLOSED SYSTEM SEWER WHICH GOES TO THEIR WATER TREATMENT PLANT.

DRIVER HAD SIGNED BILL OF LADING AND UNLOADER GAVE BILL OF LADING PAPERS BACK TO DRIVER. DRIVER CHECKED FOR PLACE CARDS AND ASSURED LOADING WAS FINISHED. HE STARTED TO PULL OUT FROM TASK. PULLED UP 4 FEET AND HAD TO BACK UP. CHECKED MIRRORS AND SAW LOADING HOSE SLIDE OUT OF DOME. HE SHUT THE LOADING VALVE OFF. PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN LOADING AREA PIT. SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED, SOAKED UP WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO DRUMS.

AFTER DRIVER SPOTTED TRAILER AND SAFETY CHECK OFF WAS COMPLETED, UNLOADER HOOKED UP HIS DISCHARGE AND VAPOR LINES AND DRIVER STARTED TO PUMP. PRODUCT WAS UNLOADING FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES AND VAPOR CAME FROM FITTING. DRIVER SHUT OFF PUMP. UNLOADER PURGED LINES BACK INTO CARGO TANK, CHECK FITTINGS AND SAW NO VAPOR. DISCONNECTED HOSE AND RETURNED TRAILER TO SHIPPER FOR REPAIRS. INSPECTION REVEALED GASKET WAS BAD AND FITTING COULD HAVE BEEN LOOSE.
PAILS WERE FOUND LEAKING THAT HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY FREIGHT THAT HAD FALLEN ON THEM. THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

DOWX 7983, RAILROAD TANKCAR, CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS SET OUT AT COOPER NATURAL RESOURCES PASS TRACK, BROWNFIELD, TX, 7/13/98 FOR FURTHERANCE TO SEAGRAVES,TX. CONSIGNEE REAGENT CHEMICAL. BROWNFIELD POLICE DEPT. NOTICED AN EARLY MORNING FOG APPROXIMATELY 4:00 A.M. ON 7/18/98. MENTION WAS MADE DURING SHIFT CHANGE AND AN OFFICER LOCATED TANK CAR LEAKING. IT WAS APPROXIMATELY 6:00 A.M. WHEN FIRST NOTIFICATION OF LEAK WAS ISSUED. TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED . EVACUATION OF AREA WAS INITIATED AT THE REQUEST OF BROWNFIELD POLICE CHIEF APPROXIMATELY 7:00 A.M. REAGENT CHEMICAL RESPONDED WITH HAZMAT PERSONNEL. TANK CAR WAS TRANSFERRED TO ACID HAULING TRUCKS AND REMOVED FROM LOCATION.

CUSTOMER'S TANK DID NOT HOLD THE FULL DELIVERY. DRIVER WAS IN A ATTENDANCE AT TANK TRUCK. CUSTOMER SUPERVISOR, MARCUS POWELL, CAME OUT OF BUILDING WITH PRODUCT ON HIS SHOULDER AND IN HIS HAIR. HE HAD BEEN STANDING NEXT TO HIS INDOOR STORAGE TANK WHEN IT OVERFLOWED KEN HAMILTON OF CARRIER'S GEISMER, LA FACILITY SPOKE WITH MR. POWELL THE NEXT DAY, AND LEARNED THAT HE HAD GOTTEN SOME MATERIAL IN HIS EYES ALSO, BUT HAD WASHED IT OUT IN THE COMPANY SAFETY EYEWASH. MR.POWELL WAS ALSO TAKEN TO PLANT DOCTOR FOR EXAMINATION, SENT HOME TO CHANGE CLOTHING AND WASH HIS HAIR, AND RETURNED TO WORK SAME DAY. NO LOST TIME, NO INJURY. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CUSTOMER PERSONAL. NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAY.

THE CUSTOMER UNLOADING VALVE WAS STUCK AND THE HOSES HAD TO BE DISCONNECTED IN ORDER TO CHECK IT. WHEN THE HOSES WERE DISCONNECTED TO OBTAIN ACCESS TO VALVE, SOME PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT OF THE CONNECTION. THE PRODUCT HIT THE GROUND AND THE CARRIER TRACTOR VEHICLE. CUSTOMER PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAY AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

CONSIGNEE CALLED OUT THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEAN UP CREW TO CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT. THE EMERGENCY CREW EVACUATED ALL EMPLOYEES IN THE DOCK AREA. THE CLEAN UP CREW DETERMINED THAT TWO DRUMS WERE LEAKING AROUND BOTTOM RIM. THE DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER. THE SPILL AREA CLEANED AND THE PTL DRIVER WAS ALLOWED TO  CONTINUE THE FOLLOWING MORNING. THE SHIPPER WAS GOING TO BE RESPONSIBLE FOR GETTING THE 2 OVERPACKED DRUMS BACK TO THEIR FACILITY.

column168: 7/24/98 AT 4:45 P.M., TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS DRIVING NORTH ON HWY 27. FOUR MILES NORTH OF MARSHALL, AR WITH A TRANSPORT LOAD OF FUEL. THREE CARS WERE FOLLOWING, THEN TWO TURNED OFF. ONE CAR WAS BEHIND TRANSPORT FOLLOWING AT A SAFE DISTANCE AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT. DRIVER WAS TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 25-30 MPH UP A (APPROXIMATELY) 7% GRADE TOWARD A LEFT HAND CURVE. STARTED THE CURVE AND FELT TRUCK TURNING OVER TO THE RIGHT HAND SIDE. DRIVER DOESN'T REMEMBER ANYTHING ELSE UNTIL RIDING TO THE HOSPITAL IN AN AMBULANCE. DOESN'T KNOW WHAT CAUSED THE ACCIDENT. HE HAD A FULL NIGHTS SLEEP AND HAD JUST HAD A SANDWICH AND COFFEE AT DENARD (20 MILES SOUTH). DRIVER HAS BEEN INTERVIEWED AND IT WAS RECOMMENDED THAT HE ATTEND A COMPANY SPONSORED SAFETY COURSE.

column168: CHEVRON DRIVER WAS LOADING ON LANE #3 ON THE WEST LOADING RACK AND COULD NOT GET PLUS PUMP TO START.  THE DRIVER ADVISED THE TERMINAL OPERATOR WHO ADVISED THE DRIVER TO STOP LOADING WHILE HE CHECKED THE SYSTEM.  A SECOND CHEVRON DRIVER PULLED ONTO LANE #2 AND BEGAN LOADING HIS #1 COMPARTMENT WITH 3500 GALLONS OF REGULAR UNLEADED.  JUST AFTER THE DRIVER ON LANE #2 STARTED LOADING THE OPERATOR RESET THE ENTIRE RACK.  WHEN THE OPERATOR RESET THE RACK THE UNLEADED ON LANE #2 SHUTDOWN AND THE GALLONS LOADED DISAPPEARED FROM THE METER SCREEN.  THE DRIVER ON LANE #2 DID NOT KNOW HOW MANY GALLONS HAD BEEN LOADED, THE OPERATOR CLIMBED THE TRAILER ON LANE #2 AND DETERMINED ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AT THE LOADING RACK AND WASHED DOWN TO THE O/W SEPARATOR. RECOMMENDATIONS: 1.  TRAIN OPERATORS AND DRIVERS ON THE PROCEDURES FOR RESETTING THE RACK.  2.  TRAIN OPERATORS AND DRIVERS ON PROPER PROCEDURES FOR DEALING WITH PARTIALLY LOADED COMPARTMENTS.  3.  DETERMINE WHY SCULLY FAILED.

OUR DRIVER WAS NOT CHARGED WITH ANY VIOLATIONS.  DUE TO THE OTHER DRIVER BEING THROWN OUT OF HER CAR, SHE DIED FROM INJURIES SUSTAINED FROM THE ACCIDENT NOT FROM ANY RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED AND PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP.

column168: ON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE, DRIVER DISCOVERED MATERIAL COLLECTED ON THE HEAD OF ONE DRUM COMING FROM A LOOSE BUNG.  CONSIGNEE REFUSED.  BUNG WAS TIGHTENED, HEAD WAS DRIED OFF AND DRUM  RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

DURING TRANSIT, THE STRAPS THE DRIVER HAD USED TO SECURE THE LOAD CAME LOOSE.  THIS CAUSED 83 55-GALLON DRUMS OF MATERIAL THAT HE WAS HAULING TO SHIFT. THIS RESULTED IN THE HOOK AT THE END OF THE STRAP TO BECOME IMBEDDED INTO THE SIDE OF ONE DRUM NEAR ITS BOTTOM LIP.  THE PUNCTURE RELEASE APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO LEAK ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  HAZPAK, INC WAS CONTRACTED AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  THEY CLEANED THE LEAKED MATERIAL FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM. THE DRIVER WILL RECEIVE ADDITIONAL INSTRUCTION ON BLOCKING AND BRACING.

column168: DRIVER PRESENTED ISO-CONTAINER TO THE RECEIVING PERSONNEL AT CUSTOMER.  CUSTOMER PERSONNEL ATTEND TO ALL HOOKUPS AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  THE UNLOADING VALVE ON TO TOP OF THE CONTAINER MALFUNCTIONED AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SPILL FROM THE CONNECTION TO UNLOADING HOSE.  PRODUCT DRIPPED DOWN OVERFLOW TUBE AND ONTO GROUND.  CUSTOMER PERSONNEL SHUT VALVE AND DISCONNECTED HOSES.  CONTAINER VALVE WAS SECURELY CLOSED AND CONTAINER WAS TAKEN TO SHIPPER DESIGNATED FACILITY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIR BY HOYER, USA TRAINED PERSONNEL. column168: IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING, JULY 18. 1998, EMPU 281253, DEARBORN DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1230 HOURS, SATURDAY, JULY 18, 1998, AT CONRAIL'S CHICAGO 47TH STREET YARD, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM TSI TRANSFER INCORPORATED OBSERVED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM A 55 GALLON DRUM CONTAINING AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, NOS LEAKING IN CONTAINER EMPU 281253 ON FLAT CAR DTTX 427680.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1240 HOURS, CONRAIL'S TERMINAL MANGER ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND SECURED THE AREA.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING (THE ACTUAL SHIFTING OF DRUMS CAUSED THE OVERLAPPING OF THE DRUM TO LAY ON TOP OF THE LIP OF ANOTHER DRUM THAT CAUSED THE DRUM TO PUNCTURE APPROXIMATELY 1 1/2 INCH AT THE BASE OF THE DRUM).  AT APPROXIMATELY 1800 HOURS, JULY 18, 1998, HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL, AN ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL REMOVED THE LEAKING DRUM FROM EMPU 281253 AND STORED IN AN OVERPACK.  THE BALANCE OF LADING WAS UNDISTURBED AND TRANSLOADED INTO THE CONTAINER EMPU 281604 AND SENT TO DESTINATION. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS SENT BACK TO AIR PRODUCTS IN WORCESTER, MA.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2200 HOURS, ON SATURDAY JULY 18, 1998, THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE.

WHILE LOADING 8 DRUMS OF SKNWS101 (SPENT SOLVENT) FROM A LOADING DOCK AT NAVAL WEAPONS STATION ONTO THE BACK OF A STRAIGHT TRUCK, AN INCIDENT HAPPENED.  A DRUM DOLLY WAS USED TO BREAK THE DRUMS AND THEN ROLL THEM UP A DOCK PLATE ONTO THE TRUCK.  THE SPILL OCCURRED WHEN A SINGLE DRUM WITH A LOOSE BUNG WAS LIFTED USING THE DOLLY.  THE DRUM REACHED ROUGHLY A 30 DEGREE ANGLE WHEN THE BUNG POPPED OFF. THIS CAUSED 3 GALLONS OF LIQUID TO SPILL OUT ONTO THE DOLLY AND THE LOADING DOCK FLOOR.  THE DRUM WAS QUICKLY RIGHTED AND THEN OVERPACKED USING A PROPER UN RATED SALVAGE DRUM.  CLAY WAS USED TO STABILIZE THE LIQUID AND A SOAP SOLUTION WAS USED TO DECONTAMINATE THE DOLLY. THE CLAY WAS SHOVELED INTO ANOTHER DRUM ALONG WITH ALL PPE AND A NEW PROFILE WAS CREATED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT SIMILAR SPILLS FROM OCCURRING AGAIN ALL CHEMISTS AND DRIVERS ARE CHARGED WITH PHYSICALLY INSPECTING AND TIGHTENING ALL BOLTS AND OR BUNG ON ALL CONTAINERS PRIOR TO LOADING.  ALL CONTAINERS ARE TO BE INSPECTED FOR DRUM INTEGRITY, DRUM CONDITION, AND PROPER POPS PACKAGING.

DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER DURING A ROUTINE STOP WITH THE LOAD. AFTER ISOLATION AND CONTAINMENT OF THE UNIT, THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE BILL WAS CALLED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. CENTRAL STATES ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO PROVIDE SPILL REMEDIATION. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT SEVERAL PAILS OF ETHANOLAMINE SOLUTION, A MILD CORROSIVE, HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY THE WEIGHT OF OTHER FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP OF IT. THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE REMOVED AND THE LOAD REWORKED AND RE SECURED. DAMAGED CONTAINERS AND SPILL RESIDUE WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND ARRANGEMENTS FOR DISPOSAL MADE BY THE SHIPPER.

A PAIL OF AMINOPHENOLS, A CLASS 6.1, PG III LIQUID HAD A SMALL HOLE RUBBED ON THE BOTTOM OF THE PAIL. THERE WAS SOME LEAKAGE. THE PAIL WAS TURNED TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY PAIL TO RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

UPON ROUTINE INSPECTION OF LOAD, DRIVER NOTICED MOISTURE IN THE TRAILER FLOOR. A CREW WAS SENT TO THE TRAILER . THEY FOUND ONE DRUM LEAKING INSIDE TRAILER. LESS THAN ONE GALLON SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. CREW CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL AND OVERPACKED THE DRUM. THE DESIGNATED FACILITY DISPOSED OF THE SPILL DEBRIS.

WHILE ENROUTE TO THE CONSIGNEE, THE DRIVER SUSPECTED A TRAILER FAILURE AND STOPPED TO INVESTIGATE.  DURING THE ENSUING SAFETY INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE, A SMALL LEAK WAS DETECTED.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIPS TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  THE MATLACK CORPORATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS ACTIVATED, A REPLACEMENT TANK TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED AND EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICES, ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS, WERE MOBILIZED TO THE SCENE.  THE CARGO WAS TRANSFERRED, UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE OKLAHOMA STATE POLICE, AND DELIVERED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THE FAILED TRAILER WILL BE CLEANED AND THE INSPECTED AT A CERTIFIED REPAIR FACILITY TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

column168: PERSONNEL WORKING AT THE DANVILLE YARD DETECTED A NOXIOUS ODOR IN THE AREA AROUND THE YARD. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND TOLD THAT THERE MIGHT BE A NATURAL GAS LEAK IN THE AREA. WHEN FIRE FIGHTERS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO NATURAL GAS LEAK, THEY BEGAN INVESTIGATING. DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT OFFICIALS DID NOT KNOW THE CAUSE OF THE ODOR, THEY BEGAN A PRECAUTIONARY EVACUATION OF THE CSXT YARD AND SEVERAL ADJACENT BUSINESSES. THE FIRE FIGHTERS ADVISED THE CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT THAT THE ODOR IN QUESTION WAS SULFUR LIKE (ROTTEN EGGS). THE CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MGR. ADVISED THE FIRE FIGHTERS THAT THERE WERE TWO CARS OF MOLTEN SULFUR IN THE YARD AND THEY COULD BE THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. THE FIRE FIGHTERS CHECKED THE AREA AROUND THE SULFUR CARS AND DETERMINED THAT ONE CAR WAS EMITTING A SMALL VAPOR. AS SOON AS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR WAS DETERMINED THE EVACUATION OF THE AREA WAS LIFTED AND THE YARD RESUMED NORMAL OPERATIONS. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT ALL EIGHT OF THE MANWAY LID BOLTS WERE LOOSE LEAVING A GAP BETWEEN THE LID AND THE MANWAY NOZZLE ALLOWING VAPORS (ODOR) TO ESCAPE FROM THE CAR. THERE WAS SOME EVIDENCE OF MINOR PRODUCT SPILLAGE ON THE CAR BODY, BUT THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF SPILLAGE ON THE GROUND.

THE TERMINAL MANAGER AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN CHARLESTON, SC, REPORTED A WHITE POWDER HAD BEEN SPILLED IN THE TRACK IN THE YARD. HE HAD NO IDEA WHEN IT WAS SPILLED OR FROM WHAT RAIL CAR. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS GROUP SENT AN EMERGENCY RESPOND CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE. THE CONTRACTOR PERFORMED SOME FIELD TESTS AND DETERMINED MATERIAL WAS SODIUM HYDROXIDE BEADS. THE CONTRACTOR RECOVERED THE SPILL MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS. CITRIC ACID WAS PLACED IN THE SPILL AREA TO NEUTRALIZE ANY RESIDUE PRODUCT. UNABLE TO IDENTIFY THE CAR THAT RELEASED MATERIAL. NO OTHER SIGN OF MATERIAL IN TRACK INTO OR OUT OF YARD. MATERIAL BEING TEMPORARILY STOCK PILED AT YARD PENDING PROPER DISPOSAL.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: RCRX 1103 HAD A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP. THE COMMODITY WAS HYDROCHLORIC ACID. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. CET ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED ON BEHALF OF THE SHIPPER AND FOUND THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE. CET SECURED THE BOLTS AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER. DRUM OF RESIN WAS FOUND WITH A SMALL PUNCTURE NEAR TOP CHIME. THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO A TANK THAT DID NOT HAVE ANY WAY OF RECORDING THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IT CONTAINED. HE WAS ASSURED THAT THE PRODUCT WOULD FIT. THE TANK WAS OVER-FILLED RESULTING IN THE 35 GALLON SPILL. THE TANK WAS LOCATED IN A CEMENT CONTAINMENT AREA. ALL THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED BY USE OF SPILL PADS AND REMOVAL OF LIQUID PRODUCT. THE LIQUID PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE LOADING FACILITY. FROM THERE IT WAS RETURNED TO THE REFINERY FOR RE-PROCESSING. AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, THE DRIVER WAS REMINDED THAT HE SHOULD NEVER UNLOAD INTO "BLIND" TANKS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER HOOKED UP OPENED VALVES ON THE TANK. THERE WERE NO LEAKS, EVERYTHING CHECKED OUT OKAY. WHILE PUMPING THE LOAD OFF, ONE OF THE EARS ON THE DISCHARGE CONNECTION TO THE CUSTOMER LINE CAME LOOSE CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN HIS OPERATION AND REPAIRED THE PROBLEM. SPILL WAS CLEANED BY THE CONSIGNEE.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: ON FRIDAY THE 14TH OF AUGUST, AT 1403 HOURS, MANAGER RODABOUGH RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM MR. DAVID GILSON, MANAGER OF SHIPPING AND RECEIVING, AT ENVIROCARE OF UTAH, INC. HE REPORTS THAT THEY RECEIVED SOME 18 DIFFERENT CARS OVER A PERIOD OF TIME FROM JULY 20TH TO JULY 31ST. ALL 18 CARS LEAKED, SOME MORE THAN OTHERS. ALL LEAKS WERE MINOR NOT MORE THAN ONE LITER. THE CARS CONTAINED VARIOUS AMOUNTS REPORTED IN POUNDS PER CAR, OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY, 7 UN2912 RADIONUCLIDES, APPARENTLY LOADED WITH CONSIDERABLE MOISTURE, THIS IN OPPOSITION TO WHAT THE MANIFEST STATED. HE REPORTS FURTHER THAT ALL LEAKING COMMODITY HAD BEEN CLEANED UP AND ALL CARS HAD BEEN MOVED INTO THEIR RESTRICTED AREA AND WERE PROCESSED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THEIR 11E. (2) LICENSE AND THAT NO CARS REMAINED IN AN AREA OF FREE PUBLIC ACCESS. THE CARS WERE DECONTAMINATED AT THEIR FACILITY AND HAVE BEEN RELEASED TO UP UPON DETERMINATION THAT THEY WERE IN AN UNRESTRICTED RELEASE CONDITION. THEY FURTHER STOPPED ALL SHIPMENT OF THIS PRODUCT FROM THEIR SHIPPER (ZHAGRUS ENVIRONMENTAL INC) UNTIL THEY PROVIDED A CORRECTIVE ACTION PLAN, WHICH THEY HAVE COMPLETED. SHIPPING OPERATIONS COMMENCED ONCE AGAIN ON 8/11/98. IT IS ANTICIPATED THAT THIS PROBLEM HAS BEEN SOLVED BETWEEN ENVIROCARE AND ZHAGRUS, WITH NO FURTHER INVOLVEMENT OF THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD. MANAGER RODABOUGH MADE NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC, INFORMING MR. CHRIS YOUNG OF THE PRECEDING REPORT. MR. YOUNG ASSIGNED CASE #74810 AND NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER.

column168: ON FRIDAY THE 14TH OF AUGUST AT 1403 HR. MGR RODABOUGH RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM MR. DAVID GILSON , MGR OF SHIPPING AND RECEIVING, AT ENVIROCARE OF UTAH, INC.  HA REPORTS THAT THEY RECEIVED SOME 18 DIFFERENT CARS OVER A PERIOD OF TIME FROM 7/20/998 TO 7/31/98.  ALL 18 CARS LEAKED, SOME MORE THAN OTHERS, ALL LEAKS WERE MINOR AND NOT MORE THAN 1 LITER. THE CARS CONTAINED VARIOUS AMOUNTS, REPORTED IN POUNDS PER CAR, OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY 7 UN2912 RADIONUCLIDES,  APPARENTLY LOADED WITH CONSIDERABLE MOISTURE, THIS IN OPPOSITION TO WHAT THE MANIFEST STATED. HE REPORTS THAT ALL LEAKING COMMODITY HAD BEEN MOVED INTO THEIR RESTRICTED AREA AND WERE PROCESSED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THEIR 11e. (2) LICENSE AND THAT NO CARS REMAIN IN THE AREA OF FREE PUBLIC ACCESS. THE CARS WERE DECONTAMINATED AT THEIR FACILITY AND HAVE BEEN RELEASED TO UP UPON DETERMINATION THAT THEY WERE IN AN UNRESTRICTED RELEASE CONDITION. THEY FURTHER STOPPED ALL SHIPMENT OF THIS PRODUCT FROM THEIR SHIPPER (ZHAGRUS ENVIRONMENTAL INC.) UNTIL THEY PROVIDED A CORRECTIVE ACTION PLAN, WHICH THEY HAVE COMPLETED. SHIPPING OPERATIONS COMMENCED ONCE AGAIN ON 8/11/98. IT IS ANTICIPATED THAT THIS PROBLEM HAS BEEN SOLVED, BETWEEN ENVIROCARE AND ZHAGRUS, WITH NO FURTHER INVOLVEMENT OF THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD. MGR RODABOUGH MADE NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC, INFORMING MR CHRIS YOUNG OF THE PRECEDING REPORT. MR. YOUNG ASSIGNED CASE # 74810 AND NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER.

A ONE VEHICLE ACCIDENT JUST OCCURED ON US HWY 62-412; THE WESTBOUND LANE OF TRAFFIC WAS PARTIALLY BLOCKED.  V-1, FAILLA, WAS TRAVELING WEST ON US HWY 62-412.  V-1 HAD STOPPED TO YIELD FOR TRAFFIC AHEAD OF HIM.  V-3 ROC, AND V-4 MAGNESS, WERE BOTH TRAVELING EAST ON US HWY 62-412.  V-3 AND V-4 WERE BOTH TRAVELING PAST THE ACCIDENT SCENE THAT JUST OCCURED.  V-2 GULUTZO WAS TRAVELING WEST ON US HWY 62-412.  V-2 TRAVELED AROUND THE CURVE ON THE WET HIGHWAY, SAW V-1 STOPPED IN THE ROADWAY, BEHIND THE FIRST ACIDENT.  V-2 APPLIED HIS BRAKES TO STOP, SLID SIDEWAYS CROSSING INTO THE EAST BOUND LANE, COLLIDING INTO THE LEFT SIDE OF V-3.  V-3 SPUN SIDEWAYS INTO A PRIVATE DRIVEWAY AND CAME TO REST FACING NORTH.  V-2 CONTINUED TO SPIN ON THE ROADWAY, WITH THE REAR OF HIS TRUCK COLLIDING WITH V-1.  V-1 ROLLED FORWARD AND CAME TO REST IN THE NORTH DITCH, FACING NORTH.  V-2 CONTINUED TO SPIN OUT OF CONTROL ON THE HIGHWAY, COLLIDING WITH V-4 IN THE LEFT REAR SIDE.  V-4 SPUN AROUND AND INTO THE DITCH ON THE SOUTH SIDE, AND CAME TO REST FACING NORTH.  V-2 CONTINUED TO TRAVEL OUT OF CONTROL AND TRAVELED INTO THE SOUTH DITCH COLLIDING WITH AT TREE, SPINNING AROUND AND CAME TO REST AGAINST ANOTHER TREE, FACING NORTH.  GULOTZO NUCO2 DRIVER HAS ATTENDED MIDSOUTH SAFETY COUNCIL SAFE DRIVING COURSE PRIOR TO RETURNING TO WORK.

MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED CORRIDOR MANAGER ALLEN (402-636-7442) TO DETERMINE TRAIN CREWS OBSERVATIONS OF THE LEAK AND WAS ADVISED THAT PRODUCT WAS COMING OUT OF THE VALVE CABINET.  MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED SHIPPER, AIR LIQUIDE, JOE WALTERS (713-824-8000) TO ADVISE SITUATION.  MT. WALTERS ADVISED THAT HE WOULD DISPATCH A COMPANY TECHNICIAN TO CHECK THE CAR WHICH MANAGER TUFTS ADVISED WAS SET OUT AT GOODWINE, IL ON THE SIDING.  MANAGER TUFTS WAS CONTACTED MY MR. DAVID GOBOO, AIR LIQUIDE, AND ADVISED THAT A TECHNICIAN WOULD BE RESPONDING FROM CHICAGO AREA AND THAT THE TECHNICIAN WOULD CONTACT MANAGER TUFTS TO ADVISE STATUS.  AT 1415 HRS, TOM KROMSCHROEDER RE-CONTACTED MANAGER TUFTS AND ADVISED THAT HE WAS IN THE GOODWINE AREA AND WOULD BE CHECKING OUT THE CONDITION OF THE CAR.  AT 1616 HRS, MR. KROMSCHOEDER RE-CONTACTED MANAGER TUFTS AND ADVISED THAT HE FOUND THAT LIQUID ARGON HAD BEEN LEAKING OUT OF THE VALVE CABINET DUE TO THE LIQUID VALVE BEING PARTIALLY OPEN.  HE ALSO DETERMINED HE REATTACHED.  BE BLED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR DOWN TO 20 LBS, AND ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS HOT AND THAT IT NEEDED TO BE MOVED AS SOON AS POSSIBLE TO DOLTON FOR DELIVERY.  AT 1620 HRS., MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED THE CORRIDOR MANAGER, ALLEN, AND REQUESTED THAT THE CAR BE PICKED UP AND MOVED AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. ALLEN ADVISED HE WOULD MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE A TRAIN PICK UP THE CAR AS SOON AS POSSIBLE.  MANAGER TUFTS ADVISED THE RMCC DISPATCHER CONCERNING ALL EVENTS AT 1625 HRS, AND THE INCIDENT WAS TERMINATED. MANAGER CTS RICHARD TUFTS WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC DISPATCHER ON 7/8/98 AT 1924 HRS THAT CAR #GATX 27297 CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM AT FINDLEY, IL.  MANAGER TUFTS DISCUSSED RESPONSE ALTERNATIVES WITH DIRECTOR CENTRAL REGION STEVE BERKI AND REGIONAL MANAGER CTS MIKE SEABAUGH AND IT WAS DECIDED THAT, DUE TO AN EXPECTED EXTENDED ETA FOR MANAGER TUFTS TO RESPOND, A CONTRACTOR WOULD BE CALLED TO RESPOND AND THAT MANAGER TUFTS WOULD RESPOND FROM KANSAS CITY IN SUPPORT OF THE CONTRACTOR.  INITIALLY, MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED KIESEL COMPANY TO RESPOND FROM ST. LOUIS AND FOLLOWING REGIONAL MANAGER SEABAUGH'S ADVISE CONTACTED BODINE ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND FROM FROM DECATEUR, IL. MANAGER TUFTS REQUESTED KIESEL TO STAND BY WITH EQUIPMENT AT THEIR ST. LOUIS FACILITY UNTIL IT COULD BE DETERMINED THE EXTENT AND CAUSE OF THE LEAK.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2145 HRS., MANAGER TUFTS RECEIVED A CALL FROM BODINE ENVIRONMENTAL ADVISING THAT THEY WERE AT FINDLEY HOWEVER THEY COULD NOT LOCATE THE CAR.  MANAGER TUFTS ADVISED THAT THE CAR ON TRUCK 728 AND SHOULD BE NORTH OF TOWN.  BODINE ADVISED THAT THE WOULD PROCEED TO LOCATE THE CAR. THERE WERE A SERIES OF DISCUSSIONS BETWEEN BODINE AND MANAGER TUFTS CONCERNING LOCATION OF THE CAR AND FINALLY AT APPROXIMATELY, 2355 HRS., MANAGER TUFTS WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE FROM THE CORRIDOR MANAGER THAT THE INFORMATION WE HAD RECEIVED WAS WRONG AND THAT THE CAR WAS PROBABLY AT PANA, IL., ON TRACK 728.  MANAGER TUFTS REQUESTED BODINE TO PROCEED TO PANA AND CALLED KIESEL AND ADVISED TO STAND DOWN AND THAT THEY WOULD BE RECALLED IF NEEDED.  MANAGER TUFTS TALKED WITH SHIPPER (ZENECA) DENNIS PICKERING (931-379-1393) WHILE ENROUTE FROM KANSAS CITY AND MR. PICKERING ADVISED HE WOULD GO TO HIS PLANT TO PROVIDE INFORMATION AND SUPPORT.  MANAGER TUFTS AND BODINE ARRIVED AT PANA, IL.. AT APPROXIMATELY 0115 HRS ON 07/09/98 AND LOCATED THE CAR.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS IN FACT LEAKING FROM A BREACH IN THE TANK SHELL AND THAT THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE OFF LOADED DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE BREACH WAS LOCATED UNDER THE SKID PROTECTION INSTALLED AS PROTECTION FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. CONSIGNEE JOHN BUERKE, MET MANAGER TUFTS AT THE SCENE AND PROCEEDED TO CALL TRUCKS TO PROVIDE TRANSPORT FOR OFF LOADED PRODUCT TO HIS FACILITY IN PANA. BODINE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED TO THE BALLAST WITH SODA ASH AND PLACED A CONTAINMENT POOL UNDER THE LEAK TO CONTAIN PRODUCT LEAKING AND PREVENT FURTHER PRODUCT FROM REACHING THE GROUND.  APPROXIMATELY 0450 HRS, TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT COMMENCED INTO FOUR TRUCKS AND THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AT 0700 HRS. WITHOUT INCIDENT.  BODINE AND MANAGER TUFTS INVESTIGATED THE SITE WHERE THE CAR HAD BEEN SITTING PRIOR TO ITS PRESENT LOCATION, APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE SOUTH AND DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 450 GALLONS HAD LEAKED AT THE LOCATION.  BODINE NEUTRALIZED THE PRODUCT WITH SODA ASH AND WILL RETURN TO THE SITE WITH A TRACK HOE TO TURN THE SOIL AND NEUTRALIZE

column168: ON 7/1/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. THE SPILL WAS IN OUR "A" BUILDING SORT FACILITY, PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN, MARTIN CLIVE RESPONDED, UPON ARRIVAL HE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD LEAKING A LIQUID. THE OUTER BOX WAS NOT MARKED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE BOX HAD A LABEL STATING "COLLECT CHARGES".  THE ONLY PAPERWORK FOUND WITH THE SHIPMENT WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET, A LETTER FROM THE SHIPPER, A DELIVERY NOTE AND AN INTERNATIONAL AIRWAY BILL.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET SHOWED THIS SHIPMENT WAS REGULATED.  THIS WAS FOUND IN SECTION 14.1 (PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE, UN1210, CLASS 3, PKG OTHER FREIGHT CRUSHING THE BOXES.  THE BASIC PACKAGING MATERIAL OF THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS OF POOR QUALITY. THE INNER METAL RECEPTACLES WERE DENTED AND THE PRESSURE CAUSED THE CLOSURES TO BECOME LOOSE.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THIS TO BE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE RECEPTACLES THAT LEAKED WERE MARKED AS THE FOLLOWING: MIT INK 81K00 (POLYAMINE FATTY ACID CONCENTRATE, APPROXIMATELY 3 PINTS LEAKED OF THIS MATERIAL. ALSO CONTAINED WITHIN THIS PACKAGE WERE RECEPTACLES MARKED (MT INKANALOGUE 81A00, CONTAINING OLEYALCOHOL, ALIPHATIC, CYC LOPRAFFINIC HYDROCARBONS).  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT.

THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. PROPER SPILL CLEAN UP OCCURRED. A COPY OF THE MSDS WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER. (SEE ENCLOSED). THE FLASHPOINT IS 100 DEGREES FARENHEIT ( A HAZARD CLASS 3. PACKING GROUP III PER IATA TABLE 3.3A). ALSO THE MSDS INDICATES AN ACUTE ORAL LD 50 FOR RATS OF 370 MG/KG (A HAZARD CLASS 6.1, PACKING GROUP III PER IATA TABLE 3.6.A-REFERENCE LIQUIDS). THEREFORE TO DETERMINE WHICH IS THE PRIMARY HAZARD, WHICH IS THE SUB-RISK, AND WHICH IS THE PACKING GROUP, IATA 3.10.A, A PRECEDENCE OF HAZARDS TABLE INDICATES A 3. III AT THE INTERSECTION OF THESE TWO WHICH MEANS IT'S  A PRIMARY FLAMMABLE LIQUID AND A SUB-RISK OF TOXIC AND THE PACKING GROUP IS III. THUS, BASED ON THIS INFORMATION AND TABLE 4.1A THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME AND UN NUMBER, THIS IS BELIEVED TO BE A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, TOXIC, NOS, UN1992. THIS WAS THE SECOND SHIPMENT ON THE SAME DAY DISCOVERED TO BE UNDECLARED FROM THIS SHIPPER. AS THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR DOCUMENTED AS DANGEROUS GOODS, THIS WAS REPORTED TO FAA AGENT SEAN LULKIN. FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: THE PASSENGER OFFERED THIS SHIPMENT AS "CHECKED BAGGAGE" AND IT WAS DETERMINED TO CONTAIN AN UNDECLARED OUTBOARD (BOAT) MOTOR AND A STANDARD FIVE (5) GALLON METAL CAN OF GASOLINE.  THE CAN CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 INCHES OF GASOLINE AFTER IT WAS REMOVED FROM THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  IT COULD NOT BE DETERMINED HOW MUCH GASOLINE LEAKED FROM THE CAN.  THE MOTOR MAY HAVE CONTAINED GASOLINE (THIS WAS NOT CONFIRMED). THE PASSENGER WHILE HE WAS AT THE TICKET COUNTER CHECKING IN FOR THE ALASKA AIRLINES FLIGHT #121/182, FROM KING SALMON, ALASKA  TO SEATTLE, WASHINGTON VIA ANCHORAGE, ALASKA WAS ASKED BY THE TICKER AGENT IF THE BOX CONTAINED ANY FRAGILE ITEMS OR FLAMMABLE, PERISHABLE OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  (THESE QUESTIONS ARE REQUIRED BY ALASKA AIRLINES). THE PASSENGER STATED "NO", INDICATING THAT THE BOX DID NOT CONTAIN ANY THESE ITEMS.  THE GASOLINE BEGAN LEAKING OUT OF THE BOX (CAN) WHEN THE BOX WAS LIFTED FROM THE BAGGAGE CART PRIOR TO BEING LOADED ON BOARD THE AIRPLANE.  THE BOX HAD TO BE TURNED ON ITS SIDE FOR EASE OF HANDLING.  THE BOX WAS PLACED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SAFETY AREA IN THE CARGO AREA OF THE ALASKA AIRLINES FACILITY IN KING SALMON PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.  THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION, DANGEROUS GOODS COORDINATOR, IN ANCHORAGE; ALASKA WAS ADVISED.  PENIAR GROUND HANDLES ALASKA IN KING SALMON, ALASKA

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THE PASSENGER (MS. CLAUDETTE BRADLEY-KAWAGLEY) PRESENTED THE BOX IN QUESTION TO ALASKA AIRLINES CUSTOMER SERVICE (TICKET COUNTER) AGENT TO BE CHECKED IN AS CHECKED BAGGAGE.  THE AGENT ASKED WHO WAS THE OWNER OF THE BOX, THE PASSENGER OF HER TRAVELLING COMPANION.  THE ALASKA AIRLINES AGENT ASKED MS. BRADLEY-KAWAGLEY TO IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX.  MS. BRADLEY-KAWAGLEY INITIALLY IDENTIFIED THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX AS BEING A GENERATOR.  THE LIQUID WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE BOX AND TH AGENT AGAIN ASKED THE PASSENGER TO IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS.  THE PASSENGER STATED THAT IT WAS ONLY WATER LEAKING OUT.  THE PASSENGER AT ONE TIME STATED THAT THE BOX CONTAINED A SOLAR PANEL.  THE PASSENGER ALSO STATED AT ONE TIME THAT SHE DID NOT KNOW WHAT WAS IN THE BOX.  THE AGENT ASKED THE PASSENGER IN THE BOX COULD BE OPENED FOR INSPECTION AND THE PASSENGER CONSENTED.  DUE TO THE WEIGHT AND THE WETNESS OF THE BOX, A SECOND ALASKA AIRLINES AGENT ASSISTED IN MOVING THE BOX FROM THE COUNTER TO AN AREA WHERE THE  BOX COULD BE OPENED FOR INSPECTION.  WHEN THE BOX WAS OPENED, THE AGENT FOUND THAT THE LEAKING BATTERY WAS CONNECTED TO A SOLAR PANEL.  THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE BOROUGH EMERGENCY TEAM WAS CALLED TO CLEANUP AND NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL ACID.  THE BOX NEVER WAS ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  BOTH ALASKA AIRLINES AGENTS FELT THEIR HANDS AND ARMS TINGLING AND THEY, UPON ADVICE OF A TRAINED EMERGENCY MEDICAL TECHNICIAN WASHED THEM WITH WATER.  BOTH AGENTS THEN WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT OF CHEMICAL BURNS AND WERE RELEASED.  IN THE EARLY STAGES OF THE INCIDENT, THE AIRPORT POLICE WERE ADVISED (BY ALASKA AIRLINES) AND THEY RESPONDED TO THE TICKET COUNTER.  THE BOROUGH EMERGENCY TEAM DELIVERED THE BATTERY AND SOLAR PANEL TO THE INIVERSITY OF ALASKA AS IT WAS BELIEVED THROUGH CONVERSATION THAT THEY WERE THE OWNERS OF THE ITEMS.  THE FAA IN ANCHORAGE AND IN SEATTLE WERE ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT AS SOON AS TIME PERMITTED.

column168: JULY 7, 1998 AT 4:12PM A LOAD OF GASOLINE WAS DISPATCHED TO TOM BENNETT FOR BRONCO QUICK STOP AT 707 E HIGHWAY 152, MUSTANG, OK FOR 1000 SUPER UNLEADED AND 8000 UNLEADED GASOLINE.  TOM LOADED BILL OF LADING #0037780 AT 4:57PM AT THE CONOCO PRODUCTS TERMINAL AT 10TH AND N SOONER RD, OKLAHOMA CITY.  HE LEFT THE TERMINAL AT 5:17 PM EN ROUTE TO BRONCO QUICK STOP.  APPROX 5:45PM TOM WAS WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 152 IN THE CURBLANE ENTERING THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 152 AND MORGAN RD WITH A GREEN LIGHT. UPON ENTERING THE INTERSECTION, A DARK COLORED AUTOMOBILE WAS SPOTTED IN HIS PEREPHRIAL VISION HEADING S ON MORGAN ROAD AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED. TWO OTHER VEHICLES WERE STOPPED IN THE SOUTHBOUND CURBLAND AND ONE VEHICLE IN THE SOUTHBOUND TURNLANE - ALL WITH A RED LIGHT.  AT THIS POINT, TOM KNEW THE CAR WAS APPARENTLY NOT GOING TO STOP AT THE RED LIGHT AND TRUCK #110/TRAILER #124 WAS ALREADY IN THE INTERSECTION, HE LOOKED IN THE PASSENGER SIDE FENDER MOUNTED MIRRORS AND WAS ABLE TO SEE THE IMPACT OF THE SOUTHBOUND AUTOMOBILE INTO THE RIGHT MIDSECTION OF THE TRAILER INTO THE VALVES, INSTANTLY GOING INTO FLAMES.  TOM IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN TRAILER AND TRACTOR EMERGENCY STOP, SKIDDING TO A COMPLETE STOP, WHILE DRAGGING THE AUTOMOBILE UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER.  UPON STOPPING, TOM REMOVED HIS SEATBELT, EXITED THE TRUCK FROM THE DRIVERS SIDE, RAN TO THE DRIVERS SIDE MIDSECTION OF THE TRAILER TO CHECK ON THE DRIVER OF THE AUTOMOBILE AND SEEING THE AUTO WAS COMPLETE ENGULFED IN FLAMES, THERE WAS NOTHING HE COULD DO TO HELP OR TO EXTINGUISH THE FLAMES.  AT THIS POINT, TOM RETURNED TO THE CAB OF THE TRUCK, GRABBED MANIFEST AND PORTABLE PHONE FROM THE CAB, EXITED THE VEHICLE AND RAN ACROSS HIGHWAY 152 SOUTHBOUND TO A BUSINESS, WHRE TOM WAS TOLD THAT 911 HAD ALREADY BEEN CALLED.  TOM THEN CALLED RED ROCK DISTRIBUTING, GOT NO ANSWER, SO HE CALLED TOMMY GARY DIRECT (OWNER OF THE TRUCK). REPORTING THAT HE WAS IN AN ACCIDENT, THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE ON FIRE, THAT HE NEEDED TO HAVE TOMMY CONTACT AUTHORITIES AND RED ROCK DISTRIBUTING.  GOING BACK TO THE AREA OF THE TRAILER, TOM NOTICED THAT A CAR WITH FIREFIGHTER INSIGNIAS WAS AT THE SCENE AND TOLD HIM THAT THE TRAILER CONTAINED GASOLINE AND THAT THE AREA NEEDED TO BE EVAUCATED AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE.  THE FIREFIGHTER AND TOM THEN WENT FROM BUSINESS TO BUSINES TO WARN PEOPLE TO EVACUATE, THAT THE TANKER WAS FULL OF GASOLINE AND COULD EXPLODE.  AT THIS TIME TOM AND THE FIREFIGHTER GOT INTO THE FIREFIGHTERS CAR WENT EASTBOUND TO CLEAR THE AREA.  FROM THIS POINT IN TIME, LOCAL POLICE AND FIREFIGHTERS WERE ALREADY ON THE SCENE AND ADVISED TOM TO REMOVE HIMSELF FROM THE SCENE AND WALK TO A DESIGNATED AREA APPROX 2 BLOCKS EAST OF THE INTERSECTION WHERE THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED.  FROM THIS POINT ON UNTIL APPROX 8:00PM FIRE OFFICIALS WERE ON THE SCENE TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE AND AN INVESTIGATION WITH THE MUSTANG POLICE DEPT WAS BEGUN.  TOM WORKED WITH POLICE ON THE INITIAL INVESTIGATION THEN PROCEEDED TO S WEST INTEGRIS HOSPITAL FOR POST-

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Dropped
column168: AT THE END OF BREAKING DOWN OUR INBOUND FREIGHT, MY DRIVER APPROACHED ME SAYING THERE WAS A LEAKING SHIPMENT.  WHEN I ARRIVED THERE WAS A COOLER SITTING IN A PUDDLE WITH A STRONG RANCID SMELL.  I CLEARED MY DRIVERS OF THAT AREA AND GOT SOME RUBBER GLOVES.  I REMOVED THE PACKAGES AROUND THE AREA AND WROTE DOWN THE AIRBILL NUMBER AND SHIPPER INFORMATION OFF THE LOT LABEL.  WE OPENED ALL THE DOCK DOORS FOR VENTILATION.  I CALLED THE SHIPPER TO FIND OUT WHAT WAS SHIPPED.  I TALKED TO JIM SOOK OF ENVIRONITE SERVICES OF OHIO. HE STATED IT WAS LENCHATE, OR RUN OFF FROM A LANDFILL. I ASKED IF IT WAS HAZARDOUS AND HE SAID IT WAS HAZARDOUS WASTE.  I OBTAINED ALL THE INFO HE COULD PROVIDE ON THE SUBSTANCE (ATTACHED IS WHAT WAS FAXED TO ME) AND I CALLED OUR GENERAL OFFICE AND TALKED TO RANDY CIMMERY.  HE CONTACTED CLEAN HARBORS TO COME CONTAIN AND CLEANUP THE MESS. WHEN THEY ARRIVED THE SPILL HAD DISSIPATED, SO THEY PLACED THE SHIPMENT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND CLEANED THE FLOORS.  THEY ALSO PUT ANOTHER SHIPMENT THAT CAME IN CONTACT WITH THIS SPILL INTO ANOTHER RECOVERY DRUM.  I THEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TO GET THE INFO NEEDED FOR THIS REPORT.

column14: SR 509 N BOUND AT PORT OF TACO
column168: WHILE SLOWING TO A STOP AT A TRAFFIC LIGHT THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE, DAN BUMPHREY, SAW MATERIAL SPILL FROM TANK TRAILER.  MR. THE Tacoma FIRE DEPARTMENT THEN ASSUMED CONTROL OF THE TRAFFIC SITUATION.  THE ROADWAY WAS BLOCKED AS THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED. THE MATERIAL WAS THEN ABSORBED AND REMOVED FROM THE ROADWAY.  THE TOCOMA FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL RESPONSE TEAM AND BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL Inc.,  A WHOLLY OWNED SUBSIDIARY OF PHILLIP SERVICES CORP.,  TACOMA FACILITY PERSONNEL REMOVED THE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE ROADWAY,  PLACED THE MATERIAL INTO CONTAINERS AND TRANSPORTED THE SPILL MATERIAL,  ALONG WITH THE VEHICLE, TO BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL INC., TACOMA FACILITY, FOR MANAGEMENT OF THE REMAINDER OF THE TANK TRAILER LOAD AND THE RECOVERED MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL.  THE TANK TRAILER WAS PRESSURIZED DURING THE COURSE OF TRANSPORTATION WHEN THE INTERNAL PRESSURE REACH A LEVEL HIGH ENOUGH TO ACTIVATE THE PRESSURE RELIEF SYSTEM.  THE MATERIAL CANE TO A STOP.

THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED AT UNLOAD.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THE PLASTIC BOTTLE(S) HAD A RUPTURED SEAM WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

MGR. C.T.S. WILDER WAS ADVISED BY THE INTERMODAL RAMP FOREMAN THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING TRAILER THAT HAD JUST BEEN TAKEN OFF OF  A TRAIN. UPON INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER, MGR. WILDER FOUND THE LEAKING PRODUCT TO BE PAINT RESIN. MGR. WILDER COULD NOT ENTER THE TRAILER ON ACCOUNT OF RESIN ON FLOOR OF TRAILER ABOUT 1/4" DEEP. MGR. WILDER DISCOVERED A HOLE ABOUT 2" DOWN ON THE RIGHT FRONT BOTTOM SIDE OF TRAILER AND PUT A 55 GALLON DRUM BELOW HOLE AND HAD THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER LOWERED TO DRAIN THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER OF THE RESIN. MGR. WILDER NOTIFIED MGR. DAMAGE PREVENTION KURT JACBSON AND MOL INTERMODAL OF THE PROBLEM AND MEET WITH BOTH ON THE MORNING OF 7/29/98. NO BLOCKING AND/OR BRACING WAS USED IN THE SHIPMENT.THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS IMPROPER LOADING WHICH ALLOWED DRUMS TO VIBRATE AND CHAFE RINGS. THE DRUMS AT THE DOOR WERE ENCIRCLED BY A 1-1/4 INCH BAND WHICH APPEARED TO BE SLIT STEEL, WHICH IS NOT AAR APPROVED. RINGS ON DRUMS AT DOORWAY WERE WORN AND THE ONLY SEPARATION BETWEEN THE LAYERS OF DRUMS WAS AN 1/8" PLYWOOD VENEER. DRUMS HAD ROTATED CUTTING THROUGH VENEER AND BEGAN CHAFING TOPS OF BOTTOM LAYER DRUMS. FROM MARKS ON RIMS, DRUMS WERE NOT LOADED VERTICALLY IN LINE. MATERIALS USED TO SECURE AND SEPARATE SECOND LAYER ARE NOT APPROVED FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. CONTRACTOR CALLED TO TRANSFER THE LOAD TO ANOTHER TRAILER, MOLU 824088. NO WATER WAYS, OR STROM DRAINS WHERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. MGR. WILDER USED SPEEDY DRY TO CLEAN UP THE RESIN THAT HAD REACHED THE GROUND.

column168: AT 1930 HR ON SUNDAY THE 26TH DAY OF JULY, MGR RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY DAN AT RMCC OF LEAKING CONTAINER GSTU 514652.  CAR WITH CONTAINER HAS BEEN SET OUT AT OGDEN, FOR REPAIR. INSPECTION AT OGDEN REVEALED THE CONTAINER WAS ONE OF TWO PLACED ON THE BOTTOM LEVEL WITH A LARGE CONTAINER ON TOP, THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION WAS PLACED WITH ANOTHER CONTAINER DOOR TO DOOR, MAKING INTERNAL INSPECTION IMPOSSIBLE. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CONTAINER MOVED TO SALT LAKE WHERE IT COULD BE REMOVED FROM THE CAR AND ACCESS MADE AVAILABLE.  THE CONTAINER ARRIVED AT SALT LAKE ON TUESDAY TH 28TH AND WAS PLACED ON THE GROUND.  ECI ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO DO THE REMEDIATION.  THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED AND THE CONTENTS REMOVED, THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE IDENTIFIED, CONSISTING OF ONE 5 GALLON DRUM AND ONE 55 GALLON DRUM, TOTAL COMMODITY LOST ABOUT 30 GALLON.  THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED, THE CONTAINER CLEANED AN ALL CONTENTS RETURNED TO THE CONTAINER, WITH SPECIALIST ATTENTION APPLIED TO THE SECUREMENT OF THE LOAD IN COMPLIANCE WITH DOT REGULATIONS. PHOTOGRAPHS WERE TAKEN OF THE LOAD PRIOR TO REPAIR AND AFTER AND ARE AVAILABLE.  ECI ENVIRONMENTAL MADE ARRANGEMENTS DIRECTLY WITH THE SHIPPER APL TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP AND ALL ASSOCIATED TASKS. CHEMTREC NOTIFIED BY MGR RODABOUGH, MISS TRACY JACKSON, WAS ADVISED OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES AND ASSIGNED A REPORT NUMBER 73792.  THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: A DRIVER DROPPED HIS PUP TRAILER IN THE PARKING LOT OF THE EXXON 290 EXPRESSWAY IN HOCKLEY. WHILE PULLING AWAY THE TRAILER FELL NOSE FORWARD LIFTING THE WHEELS OF THE GROUND. UPON IMPACT, A 220-GALLON TOTE OF SULFURIC ACID BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE VALVE. A TOTAL OF 160 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED INTO THE PARKING LOT AND AN ADJACENT DITCH. THE DRIVER CALLED ARENS WRECKER SERVICE FOR ASSISTANCE, LUKE MCCALLUM DISPATCHED THE EAGLE HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TEAM, AND GARRY HILL MADE THE APPROPRIATE CONTACTS ASSOCIATED WITH AN RQ SPILL. THE OFFICIALS ON THE SCENE SUCCESSFULLY CONTAINED THE SPILL, NEUTRALIZED THE ACID, AND SECURED THE AREA. THERE WERE NO DEFECTS OR PACKAGE FAILURES NOTED UPON INSPECTION OF THE TOTAL THE REPRESENTATIVE FROM EAGLE REPORTED N OPEN VALVE AND A MISSING DUST CAP. IT WAS DETERMINED THE THE IMPACT OF THE FALL JARRED OPEN THE VALVE. THE STILTS OF THE TRAILER THAT FELL ARE UNCOMMONLY CLOSE TO THE WHEELS. EXCESSIVE WEIGHT IN THE FROM OF THE TRAILER CAUSED THE ACCIDENT. WAREHOUSE ATTENDANTS WILL BE MORE COGNIZANT OF WEIGHT DISTRIBUTION WHILE LOADING TRAILERS IN THE FUTURE. ADDITIONALLY, THE INCIDENT WAS REVIEWED DURING A DRIVER SAFETY MEETING. DRIVERS WERE ADVISED TO DROP TRAILERS ONLY WHEN ABSOLUTELY NECESSARY AND VERIFY THE PRESENCE OF DUST CAPS ON ALL TOTES.

THE LIQUID WAS TESTED WITH PH PAPER , PH READING WAS 1. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THIS BOX TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS ARE A REGULATED MATERIAL. THE SPILL TEAM OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 2-16 OZ GLASS BOTTLES WRAPPED IN BUBBLE WRAP, ONE OF THESE BOTTLES LEAKED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS (16 OZ.) .  THESE INNER BOTTLES WERE MARKED"PHENOL UN2821, CAUSTIC, CAUSE OF LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO ONE BOTTLE BEING BROKEN. THE PHENOL LEAKED UPON 166 PIECES OF FREIGHT THAT HAD TO BE RE PACKAGED INTO NEW OUTER PACKAGING BEFORE TRANSPORT. A COPY OF THIS MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. THE ENTIRE REMEDIATION OF  THIS SPILL LASTED 2 HRS. AND 9 MIN. ALL AREAS AFFECTED BY THIS SPILL WERE NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED BEFORE NORMAL WORKING CONDITIONS WERE RESUMED. ELEVEN OF OUR HAZ MAT CHEMICAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THIS SPILL. column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE ST LOUIS RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN CASHION, ARIZONA.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED SAM KEPHART, MANAGER, TRAIN OPERATIONS, PHOENIX, ARIZONA, WHO WAS ON SITE WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AT THE CASHION SIDING.  MANAGER KEPHART STATED THE ABOVE TANK CAR HAD BEEN SET OUT EARLIER IN THE DAY BY A LOCAL TRAIN.  IT HAD BEEN REPORTED LEAKING TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT BY AN UNKNOWN SOURCE, AND THEY HAD CONTACTED THE RAILROAD.   THE CAR WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE CAR AT A RATE OF 15-20 DROPS PER MINUTE.  AS THE TANK CAR WAS CONSIGNED TO BULK TRANSPORTATION, BUCKEYE, ARIZONA, THEY WERE CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO SEND A REPRESENTATIVE TO INSPECT THE TANK CAR AND SEE IF THE LEAK COULD BE STOPPED.  BULK PERSONNEL ARRIVED , BUT WERE UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK. ASHLAND CHEMICAL, CHANDLER, AZ., WAS ALSO CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO PROVIDE PERSONNEL, AS THE CONTENTS OF THIS TANK CAR WERE DESTINED TO THEIR FACILITY.  THE SHIPPER, VULCAN CHEMICAL, WICHITA, KANSAS, WAS NOTIFIED AND ALSO ASKED TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE.  VULCAN CONTACTED ONE OF THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS, ERI, OUT OF TEMPE, AZ., WHO RESPONDED WITH A TEAM.  ERI WAS ABLE TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE WHERE IT IS BOLTED TO THE UNDER SIDE OF THE TANK CAR.  BY TIGHTENING THE FLANGE BOLTS, THE LEAK WAS REDUCED TO LESS THAN ONE DROP PER MINUTE.  THE TANK CAR WAS "DIAPERED" TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL LOSS OF PRODUCT.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CAR DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE THE FOLLOWING MORNING, WHERE THE CONTENTS COULD BE OFF LOADED.  THE SHIPPER WILL ARRANGE TO HAVE THE CAR SHOPPED AND INSPECTED ONCE IT IS MADE EMPTY. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER, FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE ST. LOUIS RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE LATC RAMP.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED CRAIG NICHENS, MGR., TERMINAL OPERATIONS, WHO STATED THE CONTAINER WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT AS IT WAS BEING REMOVED FROM THE RAIL CAR.  THE LEAK WAS ONLY A FEW DROPS PER MINUTE, AND AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARD, IT WAS MOVED TOT HE FACILITIES CONTAINMENT AREA WHERE IT COULD BE  SECURED AND ISOLATED PENDING AN INSPECTION OF THE LANDING.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LATC, INSPECTED THE CONTAINER, AND NOTED NO LEAKS A THE REAR DOORS, HOWEVER THE AREA WAS STILL DAMP.   UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS IT WAS NOTED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON POLY DRUMS. THE DRUMS HAD BEEN HELD IN PLACE WITH TH E USE OF TWO STRIPS OF TY GUARD, WHICH WAS LOOSE AND HANGING.  THERE WAS A 2X6 THAT HAD BEEN NAILED TO THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER NEAR THE REAR DOORS TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL SUPPORT FOR THE DRUMS.  THEIS CONTAINER IS 102 INCH WIDE, AND THE DRUMS WERE LOADED IN A 4X4X4 PATTERN.  DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFT, IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE TO DETERMINE THE PLACEMENT PATTERN, HOWEVER, IT APPEARS THAT EVEN IF THE INDIVIDUAL ROWS OF DRUMS WERE OFF SET, THERE WAS NO LUMBER ON THE FLOORING TO SECURE EACH ROW IN PLACE.  WITH NO SECUREMENT, THE ROWS SHIFTED SIDE WAYS DURING TRANSIT, WHICH ALLOWED THE ENTIRE LOAD TO SHIFT.   ONCE THE LOAD SHIFTED AND COMPRESSED, THE TY GUARD LOOSENED, WHICH PUT THE FULL CONTAINMENT DEPENDENT UPON THE LUMBER NAILED TO THE FLOORING.  THE PUNCTURED DRUM, CONTAINING "CRW 5449D", LOST APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  SEVERAL OTHER DRUMS WERE CRUSHED ON THE SIDES AND BOTTOMS FROM THE FREIGHT SHIFTING, BUT WERE CONSIDERED STABLE ENOUGH TO BE TRANSPORTED TO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A OVERPACK AND SECURED FOR TRANSPORT WITH THE REST OF THE LADING.  THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS REWORKED AND PROPERLY SECURED FOR OVER THE ROAD MOVEMENT TOT HE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.  BASED UPON THE TYPE AND AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOST, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE ST. LOUIS RMCC, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR THAT WAS LOCATED NORTH OF PALM DALE.  THE KERN COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SITE AND HAD REQUESTED A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE RAILROAD RESPOND TO THE LOCATION.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE KERN COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT DISPATCH CENTER, AND RECEIVED INFORMATION FROM THE ON SITE ENGINE COMPANY THROUGH THE DISPATCH CENTER.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN NOTIFIED BY THE SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT, WHO HAD NOTED THE TANK CAR LEAKING WHILE DRIVING PAST THE TRAIN ON THE ADJACENT HIGHWAY.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS REPORTING THE TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AT A RATE OF 2-4 GALLONS PER HOUR.  WHILE RESPONDING TO THE AREA, DEVELOPED TANK CAR GATX 10393, WAS IN A TRAIN MWCEU-28 WHICH WAS IN THE ANSEL SIDING DUE TO THE TRAIN CREW TYING UP ON THE HOURS OF SERVICE, JUST NORTH OF ROSAMOND, CALIFORNIA.  THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR WERE IDENTIFIED AS MINERAL SPIRITS WITH A FLASH POINT OF GREATER THAN 100 DEGREES.  IT APPEARED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS HEATING UP AND EXPANDING DUE TO THE TEMPERATURES.  AMBIENT TEMPERATURES FOR THE MOJAVE AREA WERE IN THIS RANGE, HOWEVER, WITH NIGHT TIME APPROACHING, THE TEMPERATURES WOULD DROP SOMEWHAT.  ATTEMPTS TO LOCATED THE SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC PROVED FUTILE, AS THE SHIPPING PAPERS ONLY SHOWED "AGENT SP" IN SANTA FEE SPRINGS.  UPON MY ARRIVAL, MET WITH JOHN POMYKATA, MGR, TRAIN OPERATIONS, BAKERSFIELD, CALIFORNIA, WHO STATED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BRIEFED HIM ON THE INCIDENT.  AFTER HE ADVISED THEM OF MY ESTIMATED ARRIVAL TIME, THEY DEPARTED THE AREA.  THE TANK CAR WAS NOT LEAKING AT THIS POINT AND THE TEMPERATURES HAD DROPPED FROM THE DAY TIME HIGH.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE KERN COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON SITE AND WAS BRIEFED ON THE INCIDENT.  INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR, WHICH IS A DUAL COMPARTMENTED CAR, INDICATED PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED FROM THE MANWAY ON THE "A" END OF THE TANK CAR.  THE PRODUCT TRAIL DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR SHOWED SIGNS OF A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE COMMODITY ESTIMATED TO BE APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS, DRIPPING INTO THE ROADWAY BALLAST BETWEEN THE TRACKS.  INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY NOTED ALL 8 OF THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND.  UPON OPENING THEN MANWAY COVER PLATE, THE LIQUID LEVEL OF THE PRODUCT WAS ONLY FIVE INCHES BELOW THE OF LIP OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  THERE WAS LITTLE TO NO GASKING MATERIAL LEFT ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  THE COVER PLATE WAS CLEANED TO REMOVED THE EXISTING GASKET REMANENT AND A TEMPORARY GASKET WAS FORMED UTILIZING GORE-TEX MATERIAL.  THE COVER PLATE WAS THEN CLOSED AND THE SWING BOLTS PROPERLY SECURED UTILIZING A WRENCH.  INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY LOCATED ON THE "B" END OF THE TANK CAR FOUND THE SAME IDENTICAL CONDITION.  ALL OF THE SWING BOLTS WERE ONLY HAD TIGHT AND THERE WAS LITTLE TO NO GASKING MATERIAL.  AFTER CLEANING THE COVER PLATE OF EXISTING GASKET REMANENT, A TEMPORARY GASKET WAS FORM

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MGR OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  WHILE INSPECTING AN INBOUND (WESTBOUND) TRAIN IN YARD TRACK #802. SECURITY FORCES OBSERVED THE TOP CONTAINER, INBU 490327, ON A DOUBLE STACK WELL CAR, LEAKING A DARK SUBSTANCE, WHICH COVERED THE BOTTOM CONTAINER, BE INSPECTED IN IT'S PRESENT POSITION, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE THE CONTAINER FROM THE RAIL CAR.  A CHASSIS WAS COVERED IN PLASTIC SHEETING AND ONCE THE CONTAINER WAS SET TO THE CHASSIS THE PLASTIC SHEETING WAS USED TO "DIAPER" THE CONTAINER, WHERE IT COULD BE MOVED TO THE CUSTOM'S DOCK AND PLACE INT HE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE LIQUID ON THE BOTTOM CONTAINER HAD DRIED, SO IT WAS PLACED ON A CHASSIS AND ALSO MOVED TO THE CUSTOM'S DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE CONTAINED AND SECURED.  SOMEONE HAD PHOTOCOPIED A CLASS 9 PLACARD, AND REDUCED IT TO THE POINT WHERE IT WOULD FIT ON A STANDARD 8 1/2 BY 11 INCH PIECE OF PAPER, AND THEN ATTACHED IT TO THE SIDES AND ENDS OF THE CONTAINER WITH CLEAR TAPE.  INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING LADING DEVELOPED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS TO BE  18 EACH, ONE TON "SUPER SACKS" ON PALLETS, THAT WERE IN VARIOUS OFF SET POSITIONS WITHIN THE CONTAINER.  SEVERAL 1/2 INCH STEEL STRAPS WERE ATTACHED TO THE INTERNAL FLOOR "D" RINGS AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER, AND THEN CROSSED IN A "X" PATTERN, AND SECURED TO THE TOP "D" RINGS.  A SINGLE 2X4 WAS NAILED TO THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER TO ALSO PREVENT THE BAGS FROM MOVING.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD FOR THE SECUREMENT AD TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PER THE AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C.  SEVERAL OF THE BAGS WERE MOVABLE, AND GAVE THE APPEARANCE OF CONTAINING JELLO. THE BILLING INFORMATION SHOWED THIS COMMODITY TO BE A SOLID, AND IT WAS APPARENT THE COMMODITY HAD LIQUIFIED AND LEAKED THROUGH THE FABRIC MATERIAL OF THE BAGS, AND IN SEVERAL OTHER CASES, THE SACKS HAD TOPPLED, ALLOWING THE LIQUID TO ESCAPE FROM THE TIED CLOSURE. SEVERAL ATTEMPTS TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER, YANG MING MARINE LINES, FAILED DUE TO THE LATENESS OF THE DAY.  THERE WERE NO SHIPPING DOCUMENTS LOCATED WITHIN THE CONTAINER.  EFFORTS TO LOCATE THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC FAILED DUE TO A LACK OF PRODUCT AND SHIPPING INFORMATION FROM THE SACKS.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED AND ISOLATED, IT WAS LEFT OVER NIGHT UNTIL INFORMATION COULD BE OBTAINED THROUGH YANG MING.  LOCAL CONTACT WITH YANG MING THE FOLLOWING MORNING DEVELOPED A CONTACT WITH A FREIGHT FORWARDER, WHO PROVIDED THE SHIPPER OF THIS COMMODITY.  AGP WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING.  AFTER SEVERAL DAYS OF DISCUSSIONS BETWEEN AGP AND AMLON METALS, THE COMPANY THAT PURCHASED THIS PRODUCT AND ARRANGED FOR THE  TRANSPORTATION, A DECISION WAS MADE THAT AGP WOULD MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE LOAD REWORKED. THE MAIN CONCERN WAS THAT THIS PRODUCT WOULD BECOME SEMI VISCOUS ABOVE CERTAIN TEMPERATURES.  IN THAT IN INTERIOR OF A CLOSED CONTAINER REACHES THIS POINT WAS E

column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  WHILE INSPECTING AN INBOUND (WESTBOUND) TRAIN, LIQUID WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE NOSE OF CONTAINER GSTU 362881, WHICH COVERED THE "B" END OF THE FLAT CAR.  THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM THE RAIL CAR, "DIAPERED", AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK CONTAINMENT AREA, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, OBSERVED WHAT APPEARED AT FIRST TO BE PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING, RESTRAINING THE CONTENTS OF 55 GALLON DRUMS.  A SHEET OF PLYWOOD WAS AGAINST THE BACKSIDE OF THE 2X6 LUMBER BULKHEAD, HOWEVER, NUMEROUS SHEETS OF CARD BOARD AND A USED UPRIGHT PALLET WERE BETWEEN THE PLYWOOD AND THE DRUMS.  THERE WAS A SECOND TIER CONSISTING OF FIVE(5) ROWS OF DRUMS LOADED IN A 4X4X4 PATTERN IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER.  THESE DRUMS WERE SEPARATED FROM THE FLOOR LOADED DRUMS WITH THE USE OF CARD BOARD SHEETING.  THE SECOND TIER DRUMS WERE HELD IN PLACE WITH A 2X6 BULKHEAD THAT WAS PLACED ON THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER AND EXTENDED TO THE TOPS OF THE SECOND TIER DRUMS. THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL SUPPORT OF THIS BULKHEAD, OTHER THEN THE REMAINING DRUMS THAT WERE FLOOR LOADED TO THE REAR.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DURING TRANSPORTATION.  ATTEMPTS TO LOCATE THE SHIPPER PROVED FUTILE AS THE BILLING INFORMATION SHOWED EVERGREEN AMERICA AS THE SHIPPER OF RECORD, AND THEY ARE NOT A MEMBER OF CHEMTREC, WHO'S TELEPHONE NUMBER WAS LISTED FOR THE EMERGENCY CONTACT.  IN THAT THE CONTENTS WERE NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING, IT WAS DECIDED TO SECURE THE CONTAINER UNTIL THE NEXT MORNING.  ON MONDAY MORNING, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH EVERGREEN AMERICA, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA, WHO PROVIDED A SHIPPER CONTACT, SEA BRIDGE, HOUSTON, TEXAS.  WHEN THIS NUMBER WAS CALLED, IT WAS ANSWERED BY CHEMTREC, WHO AGAIN, WAS UNABLE TO PROVIDE ANY ADDITIONAL INFORMATION ON THE SHIPPER, AND HAD NO INFORMATION ON SEA BRIDGE IN HOUSTON.  EVERGREEN WAS RECONTRACT AND ADVISED TO HAVE THE SHIPPER CONTACT MANAGER COOPER.  ON WEDNESDAY, MANAGER COOPER RECEIVED A CALL FROM BDP, A FREIGHT FORWARDER, WHO PROVIDED THE ORIGIN SHIPPER.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH A  EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR FOR NALCO EXXON, NAPERVILLE, ILLINOIS, WHO WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING.  IN THAT THE LOADING AND BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS IMPROPER, NALCO WAS ADVISED THEY WOULD BE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE TRANSLOAD OF THE DRUMS.  AT THIS POINT, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM NALCO EXXON CLAIMS GROUP WAS CONFERENCE IN, AND ONCE ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING, DECIDED THE RAIL ROAD WAS AT FAULT.  AFTER SOME DISCUSSION, IT WAS DECIDED ONE OF NALCO'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTORS WOULD ADDRESS THE REWORKING OF THIS CONTAINER.  ON THURSDAY,  NALCO'S CONTRACTOR ARRIVED TO WORK THE LOAD.  ONCE THEY REMOVED THE REAR BLOCKING AND BRACING, THEY MADE ENTRY TO INSPECT THE DRUMS.  UPO

column168: ON 7/1/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. THE SPILL WAS IN OUT "A" BUILDING SORT FACILITY, PART TIME TECHNICIAN, MARTIN CLINE RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL HE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD LEAKING A LIQUID. THE OUTER BOX WAS NOT MARKED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE HAS A LABEL STATING "COLLECT CHARGES".  THE ONLY PAPERWORK FOUND WITH THE SHIPMENT WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET, AL LETTER FROM THE SHIPPER, A DELIVERY NOTE AND AN INTERNATIONAL AIRWAY BILL.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET SHOWED THIS SHIPMENT  WAS REGULATED. THIS WAS FOUND IN SECTION 14.1 (PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE, UN1210, CLASS 3, PKG III.  THE INNER CONTENTS CONTAINED 65 METAL RECEPTACLES AT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT EACH, APPROXIMATELY 3 LITERS LEAKED DUE TO OTHER FREIGHT CRUSHING THE BOXES.  THE BASIC PACKAGING MATERIAL OF THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS OF POOR QUALITY.  THE INNER METAL RECEPTACLES WERE DENTED AND THE PRESSURE CAUSED THE CLOSURES TO BECOME LOOSE.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THIS TO BE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THE RECEPTACLES THAT LEAKED WERE MARKED AS THE FOLLOWING: MIT INK 81K00 (POLYAMINE FATTY ACID CONCENTRATE. APPROXIMATELY 3 PINTS LEAKED OF THIS MATERIAL.  ALSO CONTAINED WITHIN THIS PACKAGE WERE RECEPTACLES MARKED (MT INKANALOUGE 81A00, CONTAINING OLEYLALCOHOL, ALIPHATIC, CYC LOPRAFFINIC HYDROCARBONS). THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS AND UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT.

Routine yard inspection by FRA Inspector, Gary Thompson found empty tank car releasing methanol vapors. Car shop in that same yard was informed and car was repaired. Mr. Thompson initially reported this event on report number 233 and then on follow up report number 294. Mr. Wil Gamble was in charge of this reporting at the time and was in the process of leaving Lake State Railway Company. In the process, this item was not initially reported on a form 5800.1 until now.

PIERRE RICKS CALLED AT 8:30 A.M. TO REPORT THAT HE HAS DRIVEN OUT OF THE DEPOT WITHOUT DISCONNECTING THE LIQUID AND VENT LINES FROM HIS TRUCK.  HE ISN'T ABLE TO GO BACK INTO THE DEPOT DUE TO THE RATE OF CARBON DIOXIDE COMING OUT OF THE HOSES.  HE SAYS THAT SOMEONE HAS CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THEY ARE ON THE SCENE.  SOME OF THE PEOPLE IN THE ADJOINING BUILDINGS HAVE BEEN EVACUATED.  THE DEPOT SUPERVISOR ALLAN SCHULTZ HAS BEEN CONTACTED AND DIRECTED TO GO TO THE DEPOT IMMEDIATELY (HE IS APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES AWAY) AND UPON ARRIVAL WILL CALL WITH AN UPDATE ON THE SITUATION.  ALLAN CALLED AT 9:20 A.M. TO INFORM US THAT THE AREA HAD BEEN SECURED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  ALLAN SAYS THAT THE FILL HOSES SEPARATED WHEN THE BULK TRUCK DROVE AWAY.  IT WAS EVIDENT FROM THIS PIERRE HAD FAILED TO FOLLOW COMPANY PROCEDURE (USING WHEEL CHOCKS WHILE TETHERED TO THE RECEIVER).  ALLAN ESTIMATES THAT WE HAVE LOST APPROXIMATELY 40,000 LBS OF CARBON DIOXIDE.  BOC HAS BEEN CALLED TO MAKE REPAIRS TO THE VENT AND FILL LINES TO THE RECEIVER.  PIERRE HAS BEEN REMINDED OF THE COMPANY POLICY REGARDING THE USE OF WHEEL CHOCKS WHILE TETHERED TO THE RECEIVER. ALSO TO PERFORM A THOROUGH WALK AROUND OF THE TRUCK PRIOR TO DRIVING OUT OF THE DEPOT.
